1. In C, strings are a represented as char[]. A string must always end with the last char in the array being a null-character, &quot;\0&quot;. The null character has a integer value of 0. In order to declare a string, the size of the string will always be &quot;# character&quot; + &quot;null-character&quot;. That&#39;s why the code won&#39;t run if you change the 2nd number in the array declaration from 6 to 5, since to represent the word &quot;three&quot; as a string you need the character array [&#39;t&#39;,&#39;h&#39;,&#39;r&#39;,&#39;e&#39;,&#39;e&#39;,&#39;\0&#39;], which is 6 char long.

2. When you allocate a 2d array, e.g. int arr[a][b], you are allocating a space in memory the size of &quot;size of int&quot; * a * b. In memory, this is represented by one long &quot;strip&quot; of memory. That is why you can index into a 2d array using either arr[x][y] or arr[x*a+y].

